{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512604"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:57:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:57:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11921"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11921"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.05,0.06,0.81,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4518"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52453"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4518"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11921"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37806"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"164"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6705"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12440"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42684"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52453"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-hour history of severe headache. The pain started gradually, is now rated as 10/10, and is localized in and above the right eye. He reports similar episodes over the past three weeks, occurring twice daily, lasting 45-60 minutes each time. During these episodes, he experiences blurry vision, feels restless and paces around. He has tried various NSAIDs, including indomethacin that he got from his mother, but the pain did not respond. He is a smoker with no significant medical history. His father died of a stroke a few months ago, which has made him anxious about his symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Neurological examination is normal between headache episodes. Fundoscopy reveals no papilledema and visual acuity is normal. On close inspection, there is mild conjunctival injection, and increased tearing of his right eye. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paroxysmal hemicrania","Migraine with aura","Trigeminal neuralgia","Cluster headache","Hemicrania continua"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ecluster headache\u003C/strong\u003E. Key features include severe unilateral pain localized around the eye, associated subtle ipsilateral autonomic symptoms (conjunctival injection, lacrimation causing blurry vision, nasal congestion), short duration of attacks (45-60 minutes), and a pattern of multiple daily occurrences over several weeks. The patient\u0027s restlessness during attacks and the association with smoking are also characteristic of cluster headaches. Cluster headaches are more common in men, with a male-to-female ratio of about 3:1. The lack of response to NSAIDs, including indomethacin, is also typical of cluster headaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMigraine with aura\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with moderate to severe headache lasting 4-72 hours, often accompanied by nausea, photophobia, and phonophobia. While autonomic symptoms can occur, they are usually bilateral. Importantly, migraine patients typically prefer to lie still in a dark, quiet room, unlike the restlessness seen in cluster headaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrigeminal neuralgia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by brief (seconds to minutes) episodes of severe, shock-like pain in the distribution of one or more branches of the trigeminal nerve. It tends to be triggered by light touch or activities such as speaking and brushing teeth. It does not typically present with autonomic features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParoxysmal hemicrania\u003C/strong\u003E shares many features with cluster headache, including unilateral pain and autonomic symptoms. However, paroxysmal hemicrania attacks are typically shorter (2-30 minutes) and more frequent (\u0026gt;5 per day). Additionally, paroxysmal hemicrania responds dramatically to indomethacin, which is not seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHemicrania continua\u003C/strong\u003E presents with continuous unilateral headache with superimposed exacerbations. While autonomic features may be present during exacerbations, the continuous nature of the baseline pain and the dramatic response to indomethacin distinguish it from cluster headache. The lack of response to indomethacin in this case makes hemicrania continua less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the combination of severe unilateral pain, subtle ipsilateral autonomic symptoms, attack duration, associated restlessness, male gender, and lack of response to indomethacin strongly support the diagnosis of cluster headache. The normal neurological examination and fundoscopy help rule out secondary causes of headache.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cluster headache is characterized by severe unilateral pain, ipsilateral cranial autonomic symptoms, short duration (15-180 minutes), and circadian/circannual periodicity.","Cluster headache attacks are associated with restlessness or agitation, which distinguishes it from migraine where patients prefer to lie still.","Cluster headaches are more common in men and have a strong association with smoking."],"references":["Nesbitt, A. D. \u0026 Goadsby, P. J. Cluster headache. BMJ 344, (2012).","Ahmad, S. R. \u0026 Moss, H. E. Update on the diagnosis and treatment of idiopathic intracranial hypertension. Semin Neurol 39, 682 (2019).","Ahmed, F. Headache disorders: differentiating and managing the common subtypes. British Journal of Pain 6, 124 (2012)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37806"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11921"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37806"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-05T12:24:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-05T12:26:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4518"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52453"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount